06304nam a2200757Ia 9781478093398DE-B159720240602123719.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240602t20202020ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814780933987 a10.1515/97814780933982doi  a(DE-B1597)663310  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aSOC0020102bisacsh  aMS 11902rvk0(DE-625)rvk/123554:00aFutureproof :bSecurity Aesthetics and the Management of Life /ced. by Hudson McFann, Daniel M. Goldstein, D. Asher Ghertner. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (312 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aGlobal Insecurities : 1900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword -- tIntroduction: Security Aesthetics of and beyond the Biopolitical -- t1 The Aesthetics of Cyber Insecurity: Displaying the Digital in Three American Museum Exhibits -- t2 Danger Signs: The Aesthetics of Insecurity in Bogotá -- t3 " We All Have the Same Red Blood" Security Aesthetics and Rescue Ethics on the Arizona-Sonora Border -- t4 Fugitive Horizons and the Arts of Security in Honduras -- t5 Security Aesthetics and Political Community Formation in Kingston, Jamaica -- t6 Staging Safety in Brooklyn's Real Estate -- t7 Expecting the Worst: Active-Shooter Scenario Play in American Schools -- t8 H5N1 and the Aesthetics of Biosecurity: From Danger to Risk -- t9 Securing "Standby" and Urban Space Making in Jakarta: Intensities in Search of Forms -- t10 Securing the Street Urban Renewal and the Fight against "Informality" in Mexico City -- tAfterword: The Age of Security -- tAcknowledgments -- tContributors -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2fd2star  aSecurity is a defining characteristic of our age and the driving force behind the management of collective political, economic, and social life. Directed at safeguarding society against future peril, security is often thought of as the hard infrastructures and invisible technologies assumed to deliver it: walls, turnstiles, CCTV cameras, digital encryption, and the like. The contributors to Futureproof redirect this focus, showing how security is a sensory domain shaped by affect and image as much as rules and rationalities. They examine security as it is lived and felt in domains as varied as real estate listings, active-shooter drills, border crossings, landslide maps, gang graffiti, and museum exhibits to theorize how security regimes are expressed through aesthetic forms. Taking a global perspective with studies ranging from Jamaica to Jakarta and Colombia to the U.S.-Mexico border, Futureproof expands our understanding of the security practices, infrastructures, and technologies that pervade everyday life.Contributors. Victoria Bernal, Jon Horne Carter, Alexandra Demshock, Zaire Z. Dinzey-Flores, Didier Fassin, D. Asher Ghertner, Daniel M. Goldstein, Rachel Hall, Rivke Jaffe, Ieva Jusionyte, Catherine Lutz, Alejandra Leal Martínez, Hudson McFann, Limor Samimian-Darash, AbdouMaliq Simone, Austin Zeiderman  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aBiosecurity. 0aComputer security. 0aEmergency management. 0aHuman security. 0aRisk management. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBernal, Victoria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarter, Jon Horne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemshock, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDinzey-Flores, Zaire Z., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGhertner, D. Asher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 a